it replacing hiw nto sovle that

This creates a new user object — like one complete profile/card for the person registering 👤

const newUser = {
  id: Date.now(),
  name: formData.name.trim(),
  email: email,
  tel: formData.tel.trim(),
  password: formData.password,
};
After the user fills the form, it may become like this:

const newUser = {
  id: 1783098425123,
  name: "Sanjeev",
  email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
  tel: "9876543210",
  password: "123456",
};
Each line
id: Date.now()

Date.now() gives the current time in milliseconds.

Example:

Date.now()
Output can be:

1783098425123
It is used as a simple unique ID. Since two people normally cannot register at the exact same millisecond, each user gets a different ID.

name: formData.name.trim()

Gets the name from input and removes extra spaces.

"  Sanjeev  ".trim()
becomes:

"Sanjeev"
email: email

Uses the cleaned email we already made before:

const email = formData.email.trim().toLowerCase();
So email is saved in lowercase.

tel: formData.tel.trim()

Gets the phone number and removes spaces.

password: formData.password

Saves the password entered by the user.

Then this line adds that object into the array:

users.push(newUser);
Example before:

const users = [
  { id: 1, name: "Aman", email: "aman@gmail.com" },
];
After:

const users = [
  { id: 1, name: "Aman", email: "aman@gmail.com" },
  {
    id: 1783098425123,
    name: "Sanjeev",
    email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
    tel: "9876543210",
    password: "123456",
  },
];
Then it saves the updated array into Local Storage:

localStorage.setItem("users", JSON.stringify(users));
⚠️ For your learning project this is okay. In a real website, never save passwords in localStorage—use a backend and hash passwords.


