Yes — your understanding is almost perfect 👍

Register flow
User fills form
   ↓
Create newUser object
   ↓
Give it an ID using Date.now()
   ↓
Get old users from localStorage
   ↓
Add newUser using users.push(newUser)
   ↓
Save updated users array back to localStorage
In code:

const users = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("users")) || [];

const newUser = {
  id: Date.now(),
  name: formData.name.trim(),
  email: email,
  tel: formData.tel.trim(),
  password: formData.password,
};

users.push(newUser);

localStorage.setItem("users", JSON.stringify(users));
One small correction
You are not creating a real database.

You are creating an array in JavaScript:

const users = [];
Then saving that array in browser localStorage.

So localStorage behaves like a tiny temporary database for your project, but it is not a real database like MongoDB.

Login flow: what do we check?
When login happens, we check:

Does an account have this email?

Is its password correct?

const users = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("users")) || [];

const enteredEmail = formData.email.trim().toLowerCase();

const savedUser = users.find(
  (user) =>
    user.email === enteredEmail &&
    user.password === formData.password
);
What .find() does
It searches inside the users array.

const users = [
  {
    id: 1,
    name: "Aman",
    email: "aman@gmail.com",
    password: "123",
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    name: "Sanjeev",
    email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
    password: "456",
  },
];
If user enters:

email = "sanjeev@gmail.com";
password = "456";
Then .find() finds this user:

{
  id: 2,
  name: "Sanjeev",
  email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
  password: "456",
}
So savedUser contains that object.

If no matching email + password is found:

savedUser = undefined;
Then we check:

if (!savedUser) {
  alert("Incorrect email or password.");
  return;
}
If login is successful, we save only the logged-in user's safe details:

localStorage.setItem(
  "currentUser",
  JSON.stringify({
    id: savedUser.id,
    name: savedUser.name,
    email: savedUser.email,
    tel: savedUser.tel,
  })
);
So the two localStorage keys are:

Key	Contains
"users"	All registered users
"currentUser"	Only the person currently logged in
That currentUser value is what you later check to decide: “Is this person logged in?” 🔐


 const savedUser = users.find(
      (user) =>
        user.email === enteredEmail &&
        user.password === formData.password
    );

    if (!savedUser) {
      alert("Incorrect email or password.");
      return;
    }

    localStorage.setItem(
      "currentUser",
      JSON.stringify({
        id: savedUser.id,
        name: savedUser.name,
        email: savedUser.email,
        tel: savedUser.tel,
      })
    );|what it does

This is the login checking part 🔐

const savedUser = users.find(
  (user) =>
    user.email === enteredEmail &&
    user.password === formData.password
);
users contains all registered users:

const users = [
  {
    id: 1,
    name: "Aman",
    email: "aman@gmail.com",
    password: "123",
  },
  {
    id: 2,
    name: "Sanjeev",
    email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
    password: "456",
  },
];
When someone enters email and password, .find() checks every user one by one:

user.email === enteredEmail &&
user.password === formData.password
The && means both conditions must be true:

Email must match

Password must match

If the user types:

enteredEmail = "sanjeev@gmail.com";
formData.password = "456";
Then it finds this full user object:

savedUser = {
  id: 2,
  name: "Sanjeev",
  email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
  password: "456",
};
If email or password is wrong, it finds nothing:

savedUser = undefined;
That is why we write:

if (!savedUser) {
  alert("Incorrect email or password.");
  return;
}
!savedUser means:

“If no matching user was found.”

return stops the login function there.

If login is correct, this runs:

localStorage.setItem(
  "currentUser",
  JSON.stringify({
    id: savedUser.id,
    name: savedUser.name,
    email: savedUser.email,
    tel: savedUser.tel,
  })
);
It saves the currently logged-in user separately.

Important: it does not save the password in currentUser.

After login, localStorage will have:

users
This contains all registered accounts.

currentUser
This contains only the person who just logged in:

{
  id: 2,
  name: "Sanjeev",
  email: "sanjeev@gmail.com",
  tel: "9876543210"
}
Later, you can check:

const currentUser = JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem("currentUser"));
If currentUser exists → user is logged in ✅

If it is null → user is not logged in ❌


